00:23:08,095 --> 00:23:10,137
Mark, he's real good
with woodwork these days.

262
00:23:10,263 --> 00:23:11,347
Got a real talent for that.

263
00:23:11,473 --> 00:23:13,140
- Hello, Mark.
- Ma'am.

264
00:23:13,266 --> 00:23:14,725
And this,
this is Luke.

265
00:23:14,851 --> 00:23:16,936
Luke, real book smart.

266
00:23:17,062 --> 00:23:17,937
Good with animals.

267
00:23:18,063 --> 00:23:18,938
Hello, Luke.

268
00:23:19,064 --> 00:23:20,147
Ma'am.

269
00:23:20,273 --> 00:23:23,651
And this is John,
my youngest.

270
00:23:23,777 --> 00:23:26,153
I got to pee!

271
00:23:26,279 --> 00:23:27,822
l suppose it was a long trip.

272
00:23:27,948 --> 00:23:29,490
You must be tired
after yourjourney.

273
00:23:29,616 --> 00:23:31,617
Come on, now.

274
00:23:32,619 --> 00:23:34,620
- Jonas.
- Matt.

275
00:23:34,746 --> 00:23:35,830
Been a real long while.

276
00:23:35,956 --> 00:23:37,540
Yeah, it has.

277
00:23:37,666 --> 00:23:38,541
Hi.

278
00:23:38,667 --> 00:23:39,542
This is Edvena.

279
00:23:39,668 --> 00:23:41,335
Hi, Edvena.

280
00:23:41,461 --> 00:23:43,087
You're even prettier
than your ma.

281
00:23:45,799 --> 00:23:47,091
You all gonna stand there
forever,

282
00:23:49,928 --> 00:23:51,554
I guess I can eat.

283
00:23:51,680 --> 00:23:54,515
And before you could blink,
this whole table was cleared.

284
00:23:54,641 --> 00:23:56,809
Your aunt Coral kicked
all us men out.

285
00:23:56,935 --> 00:23:58,185
I was mid-bite
into an ear of corn.

286
00:23:59,521 --> 00:24:01,856
You have-you have
never seen such a flurry.

287
00:24:01,982 --> 00:24:04,650
And then your ma and I counted
all your fingers and toes.

288
00:24:04,776 --> 00:24:06,902
Turns out you were perfect.

289
00:24:07,028 --> 00:24:08,988
And then we brought your pa in
to see you.

290
00:24:09,114 --> 00:24:11,198
l'd never seen anything
more beautiful in all my life

291
00:24:11,324 --> 00:24:13,909
than you and your ma
lying on this very table, Mark.

292
00:24:14,035 --> 00:24:16,162
Pa.

293
00:24:16,288 --> 00:24:18,664
And I helped your ma
with you too, Luke.

294
00:24:18,790 --> 00:24:22,293
You boys brought your ma
such happiness when you arrived.

295
00:24:22,419 --> 00:24:24,503
What about me, Aunt Coral?

296
00:24:24,629 --> 00:24:26,464
Did I make Ma happy?

297
00:24:30,093 --> 00:24:31,802
Especially you, John.

298
00:24:31,928 --> 00:24:34,555
Especially you.

299
00:24:34,681 --> 00:24:36,432
Now, why don't you boys
show your appreciation

300
00:24:36,558 --> 00:24:37,808
and go ahead
and clear this table?

301
00:24:37,934 --> 00:24:38,893
Oh, no, no, leave it.

302
00:24:39,019 --> 00:24:39,894
Edvena and I'll get it.

303
00:24:40,020 --> 00:24:41,812
Matthew...

304
00:24:41,938 --> 00:24:44,732
let's me and you go talk.

305
00:25:06,630 --> 00:25:10,841
l admit, I was kind of expecting
a pack of wild lndians.

306
00:25:10,967 --> 00:25:12,301
They're good, Jonas;
they're good.

307
00:25:12,427 --> 00:25:14,094
They're not gonna give you
a lick of trouble,

308
00:25:14,221 --> 00:25:15,387
l can promise you that.

309
00:25:15,514 --> 00:25:17,932
I believe you, Matt.

310
00:25:18,058 --> 00:25:19,600
So it's okay?

311
00:25:19,726 --> 00:25:22,478
You can keep 'em?

312
00:25:22,604 --> 00:25:24,897
That's just it.

313
00:25:28,735 --> 00:25:32,530
lt ain't easy to say, so...

314
00:25:32,656 --> 00:25:36,116
l'll just speak it plain.

315
00:25:36,243 --> 00:25:38,619
We can take two of the boys.

316
00:25:38,745 --> 00:25:40,788
We can't keep all three.

317
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:42,957
You and Coral
are the only family we got.

318
00:25:43,083 --> 00:25:46,001
l can't break up the boys,
Jonas, give me a chance.

319
00:25:46,127 --> 00:25:47,628
l'm asking for six months,
Jonas,

320
00:25:47,754 --> 00:25:49,797
six months, maybe a year.

321
00:25:49,923 --> 00:25:52,675
Just, just give me time
to get something going,

322
00:25:52,801 --> 00:25:54,760
maybe even meet a woman
who can help take care of them.

323
00:25:54,886 --> 00:25:58,889
Kind of like you shouldn't
have married in the first place.

324
00:25:59,015 --> 00:26:01,767
What Pearl did
had nothing to do with me.

325
00:26:01,893 --> 00:26:05,604
She was never right after John
was born, you know that.

326
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:07,690
Don't blame that backwards boy
of yours, neither.

327
00:26:07,816 --> 00:26:09,733
Told Pearl she should
never have married you.

328
00:26:11,361 --> 00:26:12,861
You watch your filthy mouth.

329
00:26:12,988 --> 00:26:14,405
You count your blessings.

330
00:26:14,531 --> 00:26:15,739
At least two of them boys,

331
00:26:15,865 --> 00:26:17,700
they got Pearl's blood in 'em
and not yours.

332
00:26:27,794 --> 00:26:31,422
l've said what I had to say.

333
00:26:31,548 --> 00:26:34,174
lt's Mark and Luke
or none.

334
00:27:12,005 --> 00:27:14,131
You're the co-pilot now.

335
00:27:20,597 --> 00:27:22,389
Pa, don't go!

336
00:27:25,352 --> 00:27:26,894
You boys be good.

337
00:27:27,020 --> 00:27:28,854
Get in the car, John.

338
00:27:32,359 --> 00:27:35,319
Good-bye!

339
00:27:43,036 --> 00:27:44,912
Pa! Pa!

340
00:27:54,089 --> 00:27:55,130
Here's your whistle.

341
00:28:05,225 --> 00:28:06,600
Did you see this?

342
00:28:06,726 --> 00:28:07,685
"Boy in the box"?

343
00:28:07,811 --> 00:28:08,686
What is that?

344
00:28:08,812 --> 00:28:11,438
Pete's just doing his job.

345
00:28:11,564 --> 00:28:13,732
That boy had a name.

346
00:28:15,068 --> 00:28:17,277
Well, l'm sure if he knew it,
he'd print it.

347
00:28:17,404 --> 00:28:20,948
Nothing we need to get
worked up about, right?

348
00:28:21,074 --> 00:28:24,702
That's my job.

349
00:28:24,828 --> 00:28:26,120
Look, yourjob doesn't include

350
00:28:26,246 --> 00:28:29,289
you getting upset
about a headline.

351
00:28:29,416 --> 00:28:30,582
l'm not getting upset
about it.

352
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:32,126
l'm just taking care of it,
as usual.

353
00:28:32,252 --> 00:28:34,503
When do you ever
bring work home?

354
00:28:34,629 --> 00:28:36,088
Barb, goddamn it.

355
00:28:36,214 --> 00:28:37,923
- l've got it.
- lt's fine, just leave it.

356
00:28:38,049 --> 00:28:39,383
- lt's my fault.
- I'll take care of it.

357
00:28:39,509 --> 00:28:40,676
lt's fine.

358
00:28:40,802 --> 00:28:41,969
There are copies.

359
00:28:42,095 --> 00:28:43,595
They're just fine,
don't worry about it.

360
00:28:43,722 --> 00:28:45,973
God forbid anything should get
out of place in this house.

361
00:28:46,099 --> 00:28:47,558
Just leave it!

362
00:30:00,131 --> 00:30:03,050
<i>Thomas Adkins!</i>

363
00:30:03,176 --> 00:30:07,513
<i>Tommy!</i>

364
00:30:08,973 --> 00:30:10,808
What the hell were you thinking?

365
00:30:10,934 --> 00:30:11,975
What's wrong?

366
00:30:12,101 --> 00:30:12,976
"Boy in the box"?

367
00:30:13,102 --> 00:30:14,186
What is that?

368
00:30:14,312 --> 00:30:15,896
lt's a news story
like any other, Tom.

369
00:30:16,022 --> 00:30:16,980
No, Pete, it isn't.

370
00:30:17,106 --> 00:30:18,232
This is different.

371
00:30:18,358 --> 00:30:20,400
This is a 10-year-old boy
who was found dead,

372
00:30:20,527 --> 00:30:22,820
and he damn sure didn't die
to make sure your rag of a paper

373
00:30:22,946 --> 00:30:24,071
doesn't go out of business.

374
00:30:24,197 --> 00:30:25,531
Look, if I can create
a little buzz

375
00:30:25,657 --> 00:30:26,990
for the few days
this story is fresh,

376
00:30:27,116 --> 00:30:28,033
so much the better.

377
00:30:29,619 --> 00:30:31,703
And if calling him the boy in
the box helps spread the word,

378
00:30:31,830 --> 00:30:32,871
it's going to help you as well.

379
00:30:32,997 --> 00:30:35,249
Let's try to show
some respect, huh?

380
00:30:35,375 --> 00:30:36,250
Hey.

381
00:30:36,376 --> 00:30:37,751
Your mother called.

382
00:30:37,877 --> 00:30:39,127
Did she tell you
that she was coming?

383
00:30:39,254 --> 00:30:40,546
She must have seen
Pete's article.

384
00:30:40,672 --> 00:30:41,922
Anytime she sees

385
00:30:42,048 --> 00:30:44,424
anything with the slightest
connection to Tommy, Jr.,

386
00:30:44,551 --> 00:30:46,510
she has to make her way
over here.

387
00:30:46,636 --> 00:30:48,053
I'll call her
and tell her we're okay.

388
00:30:48,179 --> 00:30:50,389
No, you can't.

389
00:30:50,515 --> 00:30:53,559
She's on her way, and she said
she'd be here in an hour.

390
00:30:55,687 --> 00:30:57,855
When are you gonna come home?

391
00:30:57,981 --> 00:30:59,523
I don't know.

392
00:30:59,649 --> 00:31:00,607
l'll try to make it early.

393
00:31:00,733 --> 00:31:02,109
Okay.

394
00:31:04,028 --> 00:31:05,279
Look at this.

395
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:06,488
According to this inspection,

396
00:31:06,614 --> 00:31:09,324
the building was started
in the spring of 1958.

397
00:31:09,450 --> 00:31:11,285
Who was the contractor?

398
00:31:11,411 --> 00:31:13,912
Guy named Bill Byrnes.

399
00:31:19,377 --> 00:31:20,794
Where are you going?

400
00:31:20,920 --> 00:31:22,337
I think I know his son.

401
00:31:22,463 --> 00:31:25,549
Jesus, you're talking
about '58.

402
00:31:25,675 --> 00:31:27,050
l was a kid.

403
00:31:27,176 --> 00:31:29,136
How the hell am I supposed
to remember shit like that?

404
00:31:29,262 --> 00:31:31,388
Can you give us any names?

405
00:31:31,514 --> 00:31:33,056
Well, Swede was around
back then.

406
00:31:33,182 --> 00:31:35,309
He was a foreman.

407
00:31:35,435 --> 00:31:37,102
Other than that,
you're on your own.

408
00:31:37,228 --> 00:31:38,812
They're probably all dead
by now, anyway.

409
00:31:38,938 --> 00:31:40,188
No real names?

410
00:31:40,315 --> 00:31:42,316
I told you,
they were all drifters,

411
00:31:42,442 --> 00:31:43,734
only nicknames.

412
00:31:43,860 --> 00:31:45,110
You ever see any kids around?

413
00:31:45,236 --> 00:31:47,571
lt was a construction site.

414
00:31:47,697 --> 00:31:50,115
l wasn't even allowed
to hang out.

415
00:31:50,241 --> 00:31:53,785
Look, guys, it's been real,
but I got to get to work.

416
00:32:32,367 --> 00:32:33,450
You need some gas?

417
00:32:33,576 --> 00:32:36,536
Yeah, go ahead
and fill 'er all the way up.

418
00:32:36,663 --> 00:32:38,288
Papa!

419
00:32:38,414 --> 00:32:39,873
My boy needs a restroom.

420
00:32:39,999 --> 00:32:41,750
Oh, we got an outhouse
in the back there.

421
00:32:41,876 --> 00:32:43,210
How far to the nearest town?

422
00:32:43,336 --> 00:32:45,212
That'd be Barnstable,
15 miles or so,

423
00:32:45,338 --> 00:32:46,964
just a straight shot
down 32 here.

424
00:32:47,090 --> 00:32:48,799
Thanks, much obliged.

425
00:32:48,925 --> 00:32:50,550
Come on, John.

426
00:32:50,677 --> 00:32:52,219
Come on.

427
00:32:52,345 --> 00:32:54,513
Hey, you remember the Munsel
bathroom outside their house?

428
00:32:54,639 --> 00:32:55,597
Uh-huh.

429
00:32:55,723 --> 00:32:56,932
lt's different from ours,
right?

430
00:32:57,058 --> 00:32:58,058
There's no flusher.

431
00:32:58,184 --> 00:33:00,143
No flusher, okay,
l won't flush.

432
00:33:00,269 --> 00:33:02,104
lt's not that you don't-
don't flush,

433
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:04,773
it's that there is no flusher.

434
00:33:04,899 --> 00:33:07,651
Okay, so I won't flush.

435
00:33:14,367 --> 00:33:16,368
Whoops!

436
00:33:18,204 --> 00:33:20,414
You don't have to do that.

437
00:33:20,540 --> 00:33:22,290
Oh, thank you.

438
00:33:22,417 --> 00:33:23,750
That's sweet.

439
00:33:23,876 --> 00:33:25,377
lt's not a problem.

440
00:33:25,503 --> 00:33:27,170
I suppose l'm gonna
have to start over again.

441
00:33:27,296 --> 00:33:29,756
Guess so, huh?

442
00:33:29,882 --> 00:33:32,050
You passing through?

443
00:33:32,176 --> 00:33:33,427
Yeah, yeah, looking for work.

444
00:33:33,553 --> 00:33:36,680
That's got to be tough
with a kid in tow.

445
00:33:36,806 --> 00:33:37,723
You have no idea.

446
00:33:37,849 --> 00:33:41,101
l'm sure you'll be all right.

447
00:33:41,227 --> 00:33:43,937
Let me know
if you need anything.

448
00:33:44,063 --> 00:33:46,064
Thank you.
Thank you kindly.

449
00:33:47,817 --> 00:33:50,235
Hey, I don't know
where you're from,

450
00:33:50,361 --> 00:33:53,280
but I don't like strangers
talking to my wife.

451
00:33:53,406 --> 00:33:56,908
Papa!

452
00:33:57,035 --> 00:33:58,201
We don't want
any trouble here.

453
00:33:58,327 --> 00:34:00,120
You and that queer boy
of yours found trouble,

454
00:34:00,246 --> 00:34:01,788
so you best be paying me
and moving on.

455
00:34:01,914 --> 00:34:02,914
How much do I owe you?

456
00:34:03,041 --> 00:34:06,334
- $9.57.
- Here's $10.

457
00:34:06,461 --> 00:34:08,378
I don't expect I'll be seeing
you this way again.

458
00:34:09,464 --> 00:34:10,922
I sure hope not.

459
00:34:15,344 --> 00:34:16,636
I didn't know where you were.

460
00:34:16,763 --> 00:34:18,096
I know, John.

461
00:34:24,812 --> 00:34:27,689
Good-bye!

462
00:34:58,012 --> 00:34:59,346
John.

463
00:34:59,472 --> 00:35:00,972
Hey, John.

464
00:35:01,099 --> 00:35:02,224
John, l'm gonna go in here

465
00:35:02,350 --> 00:35:04,101
and find us a place
to sleep tonight, all right?

466
00:35:04,227 --> 00:35:05,435
You'll be able to see me

467
00:35:05,561 --> 00:35:07,562
right through that barbershop
window there, okay?

468
00:35:21,786 --> 00:35:23,745
Oh, uh, howdy, boss.

469
00:35:23,871 --> 00:35:24,830
Uh, you want a cut?

470
00:35:24,956 --> 00:35:27,582
Uh, no, not today, thanks.

471
00:35:27,708 --> 00:35:29,960
l was wondering if any of you
knew a cheap place

472
00:35:30,086 --> 00:35:31,670
to stay in town?

473
00:35:31,796 --> 00:35:35,173
¢Ü Pretty red plane
in the sky ¢Ü

474
00:35:35,299 --> 00:35:38,718
¢Ü billowing clouds
go by and by ¢Ü

475
00:35:38,845 --> 00:35:40,929
My daddy taught me that song,

476
00:35:41,055 --> 00:35:44,224
gave me lots of shiny gifts.

477
00:35:44,350 --> 00:35:47,477
Your daddy give you shiny gifts,
boy?

478
00:35:47,603 --> 00:35:51,898
You walk down this street,
and you turn left on Dixon.

479
00:35:52,024 --> 00:35:55,068
Maybe if you're a good boy,

480
00:35:55,194 --> 00:35:57,112
l'll get you that plane.

481
00:35:57,238 --> 00:36:00,157
You can fly off
into the wild blue yonder.

482
00:36:00,283 --> 00:36:03,618
l'm a-l'm a good boy.

483
00:36:03,744 --> 00:36:05,620
Yes, you are.

484
00:36:07,748 --> 00:36:10,625
Do any of you know is there
any work to get in town?

485
00:36:10,751 --> 00:36:12,627
Yeah, they're doing
some new building

486
00:36:12,753 --> 00:36:14,504
on the north side of town.

487
00:36:14,630 --> 00:36:15,755
You can talk to Bill Byrnes.

488
00:36:15,882 --> 00:36:16,965
Byrnes.

489
00:36:17,091 --> 00:36:19,217
You can tell him Delaney
told you to look him up.

490
00:36:19,343 --> 00:36:21,011
- Delaney.
- Yeah.

491
00:36:21,137 --> 00:36:23,013
Thank you.
Thank you kindly.

492
00:36:33,316 --> 00:36:35,317
John?

493
00:36:38,404 --> 00:36:40,113
John Wakefield.

494
00:36:40,239 --> 00:36:42,616
John.

495
00:36:42,742 --> 00:36:44,576
Sure is shiny, pa.

496
00:36:44,702 --> 00:36:47,287
John, do you hear me?

497
00:36:47,413 --> 00:36:48,330
Yes, Pa.

498
00:36:48,456 --> 00:36:51,458
Come on.

499
00:36:51,584 --> 00:36:52,709
Wait.

500
00:36:56,464 --> 00:36:58,256
Where'd you get that?

501
00:36:58,382 --> 00:36:59,758
Nice man gave it to me.

502
00:36:59,884 --> 00:37:00,759
Who?
What man?

503
00:37:00,885 --> 00:37:01,760
Where is he?

504
00:37:01,886 --> 00:37:04,763
The nice man.

505
00:37:06,098 --> 00:37:08,642
l think I found us a place
to sleep tonight.

506
00:37:55,648 --> 00:37:57,857
<i>Can I go outside?</i>

507
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:06,449
Why are you gonna stay
in the car?

508
00:38:06,575 --> 00:38:08,576
'Cause l'm a good co-pilot.

509
00:38:08,703 --> 00:38:11,705
What does a good co-pilot do?

510
00:38:11,831 --> 00:38:14,749
A good co-pilot
never leaves his post.

511
00:38:14,875 --> 00:38:17,002
All right.

512
00:38:17,128 --> 00:38:20,797
Excuse me, uh, Bill Byrnes?

513
00:38:20,923 --> 00:38:22,215
Over there.

514
00:38:22,341 --> 00:38:24,384
You're standin' around
like it's Christmas!

515
00:38:24,510 --> 00:38:26,011
Step it up.

516
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:27,220
Bill Byrnes?

517
00:38:27,346 --> 00:38:28,388
Can I do for you?

518
00:38:28,514 --> 00:38:29,556
l'm Matthew Wakefield.

519
00:38:29,682 --> 00:38:31,266
l'm looking for work, sir.

520
00:38:31,392 --> 00:38:33,268
I ain't hiring
no more drifters.

521
00:38:33,394 --> 00:38:34,561
Too many already.

522
00:38:34,687 --> 00:38:37,230
Could use another man,
and you know it.

523
00:38:37,356 --> 00:38:38,690
What, you want him
to take yourjob?

524
00:38:38,816 --> 00:38:40,775
Mind your own goddamn business.

